##"COME BACK SAFE and be my beautiful bride. "

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Reporter, Yang Zhe, intern, Ji Zunyu

Su Jiajia, a 95 year old nurse from Guizhou Province who supports the Hubei Medical Team, is one of many young people active on the front lines of Wuhan's fight against COVID-19. As a nurse in the Emergency Department of Suiyang County People's Hospital in Zunyi, she volunteered to ride to the front line to fight the outbreak.

Xiangshou: Postpone the wedding, ride to the aid of Wuhan

Su Jiajia's lover, Wang Kunkun, a traffic auxiliary officer in the incident squad of the traffic police brigade of the Suiyang County Public Security Bureau, received a marriage certificate last year and the wedding is scheduled for February 1 this year, but a new outbreak of pneumonia threw them off course.

Seeing the situation as it's getting worse, considering the work arrangements. The couple decided to postpone the wedding and returned the tickets for their honeymoon trip to Sanya.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photo provided by interviewees at Suiyang County People's Hospital during the military parade for Su Jiajia

In the early morning of February 4, Sujiajia received a phone call from the hospital, asking if she would like to support the Hubei Front line, she did not hesitate to agree down. That night, Sujiajia quickly packed her bags and prepared to go to the front. At noon on the 4th, Su Jiajia embarked on a journey to Wuhan. Her colleagues at the hospital saw her off. Of course, there was no less "loving support" from Wang Kunkun. "in front to eat on time, must take care of themselves. Safe Return. " In the process of sending Sujiajia to the airport, Wang Kunkun repeatedly told.

After a day of adjustment and pre-service training, on February 6, Sujiajia officially began nursing at the Kong Hon Shelter Hospital. She told The Paper that the medical staff at the Shelter Hospital worked "shifts" and "four shifts" and that she worked from 8 p.m. to 2 a.m. Every night around 7:00 pm, all night shift medical staff will be assembled at the hotel, by shuttle bus to the shelter hospital.

"At the Shelter Hospital, we health care workers wear diapers to work. After entering the hospital a shift is 6 hours, plus the time to wear off the isolation clothing will need about 7 hours. "seven hours without food, water or toilet is very uncomfortable, and because of the isolation clothes, it is not very convenient, " Su Jiajia admitted.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Sujiajia in the shelter hospital

Su Jiajia told reporters that she was in charge of a 20-person Ward and was particularly concerned about one patient, a man of about 50 who had a fever of 40 C and had been given several doses of antipyretics, to no avail. In order to reduce his pain, Sujiajia thought of physical cooling method, in the shelter hospital medical resources are scarce, she back and forth five or six times in line, with a basin again and again filled with hot water, and warm towels for patients. At one point, Sujiajia could barely walk because of the steam clinging to her goggles. But for her own safety, she did not wipe it with her hands and waited for the mist to dissipate.

Each member of the medical staff has his or her name written on his or her isolation jacket to facilitate communication between teammates. After seeing the name on Sujiajia's isolation jacket, the patient repeated: "Jiajia nurse, thank you, thank you so much. ".

Thank you so much for coming to our aid, coming all the way from all over the country, when she heard these words, Sujiajia thought it would be worth her while to be tired. "everyone wants the epidemic to go away, and the patients understand the medical staff. "

20 male patients eat a lot. When it comes to meal time, it is not easy for Su Jiajia to deliver food. "20 people's portions are really not very easy to carry. " Whenever he sees Su Jiajia carrying food alone, he feels labored, several of the patients would get out of bed and offer to help Su Jiajia with lunch. Su Jiajia told the reporter that such moving, in fact, there are many moments in the work.

Meeting: A love affair facilitated by a chance encounter

Su Jiajia, who fought on the Wuhan Front, was supported by her husband, Wang Kunkun, in the rear. But when it comes to their relationship, it comes from a chance encounter three years ago. The photo below was taken on January 28,2017, after a traffic accident in Suiyang County, Su Jiajia arrived with the 120 ambulance and patched up the injured. And it was Wang Kun who came to deal with the traffic accident. It never occurred to either of them that their meeting that day had inadvertently contributed to their affair.

The same day at the scene sujiajia focused on the wounded to deal with the wound, but accidentally left the work card at the scene. This happened to be picked up by Wang Kunkun, he quickly returned to the hospital to Su Jiajia. During the brief transition, the smile on Sujiajia's face lit up Wang Kunkun's yearning for love.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Su Jiajia and Wang Kunkun in life

In two people common good friend Matchmaking Bridge, Wang Kun and Su Jiajia formally knew. One thing led to another, and the two young people finally came together. "I don't know what happened after that. We started to fall in love, " Su Jiajia said.

DEPENDENTS: On Valentine's Day, they chat until 5 a.m

Su Jiajia was in Wuhan to take care of patients during the outbreak, and Wang Kunkun was in charge of traffic control in Suiyang County. Both were on the front lines of the epidemic. But this couple separated by thousands of miles, only through the network to pass each other's thoughts and concerns. In these days, they stare at each other through mobile phone screens and listen to each other through wechat.

"usually he doesn't bother me when I'm not doing anything, because sometimes it's really hard to work on the front lines. After work back to the hotel, I will wash first, too tired, sometimes meals are too busy to eat, just want to sleep. When he wakes up, he will be notified that he is safe, send a video message, and sometimes contact him as soon as he gets off work,"Su said.

Due to the work in the Shelter Hospital is quite busy, the two people's call is difficult to set a time, "usually in the morning about 3,4 o'clock, sometimes I call, he has fallen asleep. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Su Jiajia and Wang Kunkun

February 14 is the first Valentine's Day since Su Jiajia and Wang Kunkun are due to be married, as they can not be together because they are separated. In the early morning of the 14th, Su Jiajia got off the night shift and talked with Wang Kunkun until 5 am. She told reporters it was a "Valentine's Day gift" for a special occasion.

"I hope this epidemic will go away soon. When I go home, the patients will be Get Well Soon, " Su said, reflecting on his experiences working on the Wuhan Front Line. And the news that Wang Kunkun most hopes to hear every day is that the lover of the front line is all right. He told reporters that he promised to Sujiajia, when she returned smoothly, will marry her to do the most beautiful bride.

This issue is edited by Xing Tan
